title: HIGH SCHOOLS: Spellman's Olson wins his 400th
text: HIGH SCHOOLS: Spellman’s Olson wins his 400th Cardinal Spellman High School girls volleyball head coach Jack Olson notched his 400th girls coaching career win Friday night when the Cardinals took down Falmouth, 3-0. Comment The Patriot Ledger, Quincy, MA Writer Posted Oct. 17, 2015 at 9:02 PM Updated at 9:05 PM Posted Oct. 17, 2015 at 9:02 PM Updated at 9:05 PM Hall of Fame coach Jack Olson has reached yet another milestone. The Cardinal Spellman girls volleyball team presented Olson with the 400th win of his girls coaching career with a 3-0 victory over Falmouth on Friday night. “I’m proud because I’ve worked with a lot of different kids,” Olson said. “Hundreds and hundreds of kids that are having success. That’s exciting.” Olson, who has coached at both Brockton High School and Spellman, was inducted into the Massachusetts Girls Volleyball Coaches Association Hall of Fame in 2006. On April 5, 2013, he recorded his 300th career win as a boys volleyball coach when his Boxers defeated North Quincy, 3-0. Olson’s milestone win over Falmouth saw standout Katherine Carrel lead the way with 16 kills for the Cardinals. Emma Sexton also played a major role in the win with 26 assists. “It didn’t even dawn on me,” said Olson, who’s team improved to 13-3. “Lucky 13, that was the number.” FOOTBALL Nantucket 14, West Bridgewater 6: With the win, the Whalers (6-0) captured the Mayflower Athletic Conference Small Division title. The Wildcats (5-1) only score came on a touchdown run by Matt DeLuca. South Shore Voke 30, Cape Tech 6: Vikings head coach Derek Mariani notched his 100th career victory. Senior quarterback Kyle Thompson (Hanson) helped Mariani reach the milestone with 11 carries for 98 yards and a touchdown. Richie Lobo (Scituate) carried the ball 14 times for 84 yards and a score. Defensively, James Huff had a a 23-yard interception return for a touchdown for the Vikings (4-2). Upper Cape 34, Holbrook/Avon 6: The Bulldogs couldn’t slow down the Rams. Stoughton 14, Foxboro 0: On Friday night, the Black Knights’ stout defense shut down the Warriors (5-1, 3-1). Izon Swain-Price and Ryan Sullivan had rushing touchdowns for Stoughton (3-3, 3-1 in the Hockomock League). GIRLS SOCCER Oliver Ames 4, Brockton 1: Francesca Calabraro registered a hat trick to lead the Tigers (11-1-2). Jackie Mills scored the other goal in the win. Julia Roy (two assists), Erin Fitzgerald and Delaney Benton assisted the goals. Whitman-Hanson 4, Weymouth 0: Rachel Kelly and Lauren Bonavita both scored in the first 10 minutes of the second half for the Panthers (12-0) to opening the scoring. Alexis Fruzzetti and Taylor Kofton also found the back of the net. Defense of Kat O’Kane, Kelsey Gilbert, Madison Shea and Elana Wood played well in front of keeper Skylar Kuzmich (seven saves), who earned her ninth shutout. Sacred Heart 11, Bishop Connolly 1: Junior Olivia DiBiase led the offensive attack with a hat trick and two assists. Page 2 of 2 - The Saints had eight differnt players score with senior Caroline Sheen (one assist), junior Bridget LeBlanc (one assist), sophomores Rose Crossman (two assists), Aidan MacDonald, Olivia Siveri, Regan Cavanaugh, and Zoe Volney, and freshman Emily Finn (one assist) finding the back of net. Senior Jordan Gailes (one assist) played well. BOYS SOCCER Whitman-Hanson 2, Quincy 0: Senior captain Brian McGahan scored both goals for the Panthers (4-9, 3-8 in the Patriot League). Nick Haley and Tom McGahan recorded assists, while Conor Keane notched his second shutout of the season. VOLLEYBALL Silver Lake 3, Whitman-Hanson 2: Sophia Raiche had 30 serve receives and 12 digs, but the Panthers (10-5) fell to the Lakers on Friday night. The Patriot Ledger, Quincy, MA Writer Posted Oct. 17, 2015 at 9:02 PM Updated at 9:05 PM
